HEADWORD: Emprise
<hw>Em*prise"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>emprise</ets>, fr. <ets>emprendre</ets> to undertake; pref.
<ets>em-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + F. <ets>prendre</ets> to take, L.
<ets>prehendere</ets>, <ets>prendere</ets>; <ets>prae</ets> before + a
verb akin to E. <ets>get</ets>. See <er>Get</er>, and cf.
<er>Enterprise</er>, <er>Impresa</er>.]</ety> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An enterprise; endeavor; adventure.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In brave pursuit of chivalrous <qex>emprise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The deeds of love and high <qex>emprise</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The qualifies which prompt one to undertake
difficult and dangerous exploits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I love thy courage yet and bolt <qex>emprise</qex>;⟦br⟧
But here thy sword can do thee little stead.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emprise</ent>⟦br⟧

